# Analysis of Group Policy Auditing

## @Configuration Changes
-I enabled success and failure auditing for logon events and object access within Group Policy.
-I implemented restrictions for the Ctrl+Alt+Del options menu to limit end-user access to critical system functions.

## @Applied Settings
-I configured the relevant GPOs and ensured these settings were propagated across the domain.
-In [ctrl+alt+del] options;
  *Removed Task Manager: Enabled (to prevent users from killing system processes).
  *Removed Change Password: Enabled (to enforce password management through official channels).
  *Removed Logoff / Lock: Enabled based on specific workstation security requirements

## @Log Analysis
-After enabling the audit, I reviewed the security logs for logon/logoff attempts; 4624 (Successful Logon) and 4625 (Failed Logon), and object access.
-I monitored for any unauthorized attempts to access restricted UI elements or bypass the enforced group policies

## @Hardening Success 
Confirmed that the GPO and registry-level changes successfully reduced the "attack surface" on the client side by preventing users from interfering with system-level operations
via the secure attention sequence (SAS).

## @Findings
-This allowed me to confirm that auditing was working properly, ensuring visibility into user and object access events.
-Some system changes may drasticaly increase safety level on machines
